WEBVTT

00:02.611 --> 00:04.569
[recruiter]
You're moving to London.

00:04.700 --> 00:06.093
Daytime job in the tech world.

00:06.223 --> 00:07.920
That must be decent money.

00:08.051 --> 00:09.444
[Iris] I'm not here for decent.

00:09.574 --> 00:11.446
[garbled speech]

00:11.576 --> 00:13.709
[woman]
...arms around each other...

00:13.839 --> 00:15.015
Human connection.

00:15.102 --> 00:17.060
[dark music plays]

00:17.191 --> 00:19.671
Rule number one
is look the part.

00:19.802 --> 00:20.846
[Iris] I would love

00:20.977 --> 00:22.022
to take this home
for the weekend

00:22.152 --> 00:23.023
and work on it.

00:23.153 --> 00:24.763
Okay, I'll log you in.

00:24.937 --> 00:26.504
♪

00:26.635 --> 00:27.810
You want me to make you angry,
big boy?

00:27.940 --> 00:30.682
No, not angry. Mad.

00:30.813 --> 00:31.901
What the fuck is this?

00:31.988 --> 00:33.555
You were recording us? Huh?

00:33.685 --> 00:35.470
[Iris] I just turned it on.

00:35.557 --> 00:37.428
[Brett] What the fuck for?
Huh? Blackmail?

00:37.559 --> 00:38.603
[Iris] You mad now?

00:38.734 --> 00:40.344
Oh, you fucking bitch.

00:40.475 --> 00:42.259
[Iris laughs]

00:42.390 --> 00:43.913
[Leanne] Now we know Dad
has early-onset Alzheimer's.

00:44.044 --> 00:45.741
[Iris] That sounds dramatic.

00:45.871 --> 00:49.919
[Leanne] But, Iris, I want
to get tested as well.

00:50.050 --> 00:51.747
[Georges] I'm talking a kind
of carnage yet to be seen.

00:51.877 --> 00:53.879
You reap what you sow.

00:54.010 --> 00:55.098
[reporter] Experts
are still trying to verify

00:55.229 --> 00:56.534
the authenticity
of the footage.

00:56.665 --> 00:59.276
[indistinct chatter]

00:59.363 --> 01:01.104
[Sean] Iris Stanton.

01:01.191 --> 01:03.498
Well, it was nice
running into you.

01:03.628 --> 01:05.456
It's great running into you.

01:05.630 --> 01:08.459
♪

01:13.160 --> 01:15.858
[disquieting music plays]

01:16.032 --> 01:18.861
♪

01:43.190 --> 01:44.887
[Georges] You left the room.

01:48.630 --> 01:51.154
Sorry.

01:51.285 --> 01:52.590
A little breather.

01:57.639 --> 01:59.249
[Georges] Ask me if you'd like.

02:01.077 --> 02:02.470
No, that's okay.

02:07.605 --> 02:10.173
[Georges] Got married
when we were kids.

02:10.304 --> 02:12.915
Raised each other.

02:13.045 --> 02:14.699
-[Iris] Mm.
-Outgrew each other.

02:20.444 --> 02:21.967
You still live
in the same house?

02:26.711 --> 02:28.409
Yes, we do.

02:45.295 --> 02:46.992
I know who you are now.

02:51.780 --> 02:54.913
"A kind of carnage
yet to be seen.

02:55.044 --> 02:57.264
You reap what you sow."

03:00.745 --> 03:03.400
They did an okay job
editing your face,

03:03.531 --> 03:07.665
but those deepfakes
still have a long way to go.

03:09.450 --> 03:12.192
[footsteps departing]

03:15.499 --> 03:18.633
How do you feel
about the whole thing?

03:18.763 --> 03:20.112
[Georges]
Do you really want to know?

03:20.243 --> 03:21.679
I do.

03:26.684 --> 03:28.599
Number of elected officials
around the world

03:28.730 --> 03:31.776
who never campaigned offline--
take a guess.

03:31.907 --> 03:33.474
[Iris] I have no idea.

03:33.604 --> 03:35.693
No single televised
live interview,

03:35.824 --> 03:37.739
no rallies, no speeches.

03:37.869 --> 03:41.960
All they do
is tap into people's fears.

03:42.047 --> 03:44.615
Now, once you're in office,
anyone with an algorithm

03:44.746 --> 03:46.704
will eventually find a reason
to show the world

03:46.835 --> 03:49.054
what you look like
with your hair down.

03:49.141 --> 03:51.056
[Iris] I still know
it wasn't you.

03:51.187 --> 03:53.711
That clip isn't even about me.

03:53.842 --> 03:56.323
It's about the defense contract
and the attempted employment

03:56.453 --> 03:59.239
of EU as opposed
to U.S.-based industries.

03:59.369 --> 04:01.110
How do you know it wasn't me?

04:04.113 --> 04:07.421
Because...

04:07.551 --> 04:11.555
your pinky goes up
every time you take a drink.

04:11.686 --> 04:14.341
[chuckles softly]

04:14.471 --> 04:15.516
Prim and proper.

04:15.646 --> 04:17.039
Really?

04:17.169 --> 04:18.954
Yeah, I noticed it
on our first date.

04:29.312 --> 04:32.054
Would it be too much to ask
to have you for myself

04:32.184 --> 04:35.013
for an entire 24 hours,
day and night?

04:36.798 --> 04:38.582
Really?

04:38.669 --> 04:40.236
Can you do that?

04:40.367 --> 04:41.672
Take us off grid?

04:41.803 --> 04:43.195
Watch me.

04:48.766 --> 04:52.422
[sighs]

04:52.553 --> 04:55.251
[light music plays]

04:55.425 --> 04:56.557
♪

04:56.644 --> 04:59.255
[clippers buzzing]

04:59.429 --> 05:01.605
♪

05:01.736 --> 05:03.607
[winces] Ah. Ah.

05:03.738 --> 05:05.566
-I did not cut you.
-All right. All right.

05:05.696 --> 05:06.915
But make sure
you square it all off,

05:07.045 --> 05:08.438
all right, the same length
on both sides.

05:08.569 --> 05:11.049
Don't be a baby.
That's what I'm doing.

05:11.180 --> 05:13.487
All right, do it
like my ex used do it.

05:15.315 --> 05:17.186
[buzzing stops]

05:17.273 --> 05:18.666
♪

05:18.753 --> 05:20.102
How about you do it?

05:20.232 --> 05:21.495
What, you're just
gonna leave me hanging?

05:21.625 --> 05:22.800
Well, if you know exactly
how your ex used to do it,

05:22.931 --> 05:23.801
you should do it.

05:23.932 --> 05:25.368
Hey, where are you going?

05:25.499 --> 05:27.109
-Use the mirror.
-Can't you--[groans]

05:27.239 --> 05:29.851
You're a shit-ass barber,
you know that?

05:29.981 --> 05:31.505
Can't you stay a little longer?

05:31.635 --> 05:32.767
I'll order Chinese.

05:32.941 --> 05:35.857
♪

05:42.559 --> 05:43.778
What's in there?

05:43.952 --> 05:46.737
♪

05:54.266 --> 05:56.486
Love them. Thanks.

05:56.617 --> 05:59.228
Sweet of you.

05:59.359 --> 06:01.317
Let's do this more often.

06:02.579 --> 06:03.493
I'll make it worth your while.

06:03.624 --> 06:05.016
Sure.

06:05.103 --> 06:07.715
You'll have to check
with my booker.

06:07.845 --> 06:10.239
Here, let me give you
my number...

06:10.370 --> 06:11.849
just so you have it.

06:11.936 --> 06:14.939
[light music playing on TV]

06:15.070 --> 06:16.767
Wear them next time
you come over.

06:19.422 --> 06:21.946
[man speaking indistinctly
on TV]

06:35.786 --> 06:37.875
Are people afraid
of technology?

06:38.006 --> 06:39.660
No, I didn't think
we're afraid of technology.

06:39.790 --> 06:40.965
I think we might
be afraid of ourselves.

06:41.096 --> 06:43.359
[reporter] Well,
what do you mean by that?

06:43.490 --> 06:45.187
Christophe, tell us
what you've been working on.

06:47.798 --> 06:49.583
[Christophe] Look, a lot
of today's business models

06:49.670 --> 06:52.063
are appealing
to outrage and fear.

06:52.194 --> 06:53.978
Not us.

06:54.065 --> 06:56.938
Our business model
is positive reinforcement,

06:57.068 --> 06:59.157
self-expression, connection.

06:59.288 --> 07:01.072
[Brett] You know this guy?

07:01.159 --> 07:02.944
[Christophe] What the coming
decades are really about

07:03.074 --> 07:06.295
is shaping our collective
cognitive future.

07:06.426 --> 07:07.427
[reporter] So what you're
saying, Christophe,

07:07.557 --> 07:09.298
is let's put
our brains together,

07:09.429 --> 07:11.822
solve the world's biggest
problems as a collective?

07:11.953 --> 07:13.389
[Christophe] Look, nothing much
has changed since the...

07:13.476 --> 07:16.523
No, but he's making me
kind of mad.

07:16.610 --> 07:21.310
Technology is just
the extension of our minds.

07:21.441 --> 07:22.790
[reporter] So that was
Christophe Revory,

07:22.877 --> 07:26.097
the elusive tech billionaire
of NGM.

07:26.228 --> 07:28.883
[disquieting music plays]

07:29.057 --> 07:31.451
♪

07:34.062 --> 07:35.498
[Tawny] Hi, fairy.

07:35.629 --> 07:37.587
I'll be in London soon.

07:37.674 --> 07:40.547
One of my boys is taking me
to this gaming expo.

07:40.677 --> 07:41.722
[Iris] Be great to catch up.

07:41.809 --> 07:42.723
[Tawny] Yeah.

07:42.897 --> 07:44.333
♪

07:44.464 --> 07:45.900
Hey, I really need someone

07:46.030 --> 07:47.467
to listen to my shit
right now.

07:47.597 --> 07:51.122
[Tawny crying]

07:51.253 --> 07:52.907
Here we go again.

07:53.037 --> 07:54.952
Tawny T.
going full fucking circle,

07:55.083 --> 07:55.953
like clockwork.

07:56.084 --> 07:58.913
[Iris] What happened?

07:59.000 --> 08:01.306
[Tawny] Client I started seeing
a while ago, he's--

08:01.393 --> 08:03.700
I did something...

08:03.787 --> 08:07.356
I said I would never do again,
you know?

08:07.443 --> 08:08.836
I crossed a line.

08:08.966 --> 08:10.446
Are you hurt?

08:10.577 --> 08:12.187
[Tawny] It's more

08:12.317 --> 08:14.232
"what's fucking wrong
with me," you know?

08:14.363 --> 08:16.104
Hey, don't be so hard
on yourself.

08:18.846 --> 08:20.500
[Tawny]
He had me on a leash, Iris,

08:20.630 --> 08:23.111
like a dog on all fours.

08:23.241 --> 08:25.200
It's this whole
submissive thing.

08:25.330 --> 08:27.158
It's like a rabbit hole.

08:27.245 --> 08:28.725
My knees are fucked up.

08:28.856 --> 08:30.161
I have to wear a scarf

08:30.248 --> 08:31.815
to cover the bruises
on my neck.

08:31.902 --> 08:35.427
Looks like I tried
to fucking hang myself.

08:35.558 --> 08:36.864
-[Tawny laughing]
-[Iris laughs]

08:36.994 --> 08:39.170
Why are you laughing?

08:39.301 --> 08:42.130
Just stop seeing him.

08:43.218 --> 08:45.481
[Tawny] It sounds so easy,
doesn't it?

08:45.612 --> 08:47.701
Look, if the situation
isn't serving you...

08:50.312 --> 08:51.922
[sighs]

08:52.053 --> 08:54.925
[Tawny] Someone grew up fast.
[chuckles]

08:55.012 --> 08:57.624
Yeah, I was actually, um...

08:57.711 --> 08:59.190
I've been meaning
to talk to you about...

08:59.321 --> 09:00.540
[Tawny sighs]

09:00.670 --> 09:02.019
-Something.
-[Tawny] Sure.

09:02.150 --> 09:04.021
I have this client,

09:04.152 --> 09:06.981
um, and he's an athlete.

09:07.111 --> 09:10.462
He's recovering from an injury,
and...

09:10.593 --> 09:13.378
I don't know.
He's... he's really pent-up.

09:13.509 --> 09:17.078
And his dominant emotion
is definitely anger, and--

09:17.208 --> 09:20.081
[Tawny] What do you mean
"dominant emotion"?

09:20.211 --> 09:21.996
Well... [sighs]

09:22.126 --> 09:25.347
It's linked to arousal
for him, and--

09:25.477 --> 09:27.479
[Tawny]
Gee, that sounds science-y.

09:29.612 --> 09:30.570
[scoffs]

09:30.700 --> 09:32.659
Well, it is.

09:32.746 --> 09:34.661
Yeah, it is, in a way, um,

09:34.791 --> 09:36.750
because if I can figure out
what they want, Tawny,

09:36.880 --> 09:39.056
then I get better reviews.

09:40.971 --> 09:42.669
[Tawny] You're not
recording them, are you?

09:45.759 --> 09:48.196
Tawny, I'm trying to be smart.

09:48.326 --> 09:50.241
I, um...

09:50.328 --> 09:53.114
I really like this guy,
and I just--

09:53.244 --> 09:56.160
I don't want to blow his fuse.

09:56.291 --> 09:59.250
[Tawny] It's just basic
common sense, you know?

09:59.381 --> 10:00.948
What was the question
you wanted to ask me?

10:01.078 --> 10:01.992
I don't know.

10:02.123 --> 10:04.386
Um, I'll text you.

10:04.473 --> 10:06.518
[Tawny] These are
high-profile guys, Iris.

10:06.649 --> 10:08.869
Whatever skeletons they have
in their closets,

10:08.999 --> 10:10.435
it's our job
to turn a blind eye.

10:10.522 --> 10:11.959
Of course. No, you're right.

10:12.089 --> 10:14.962
Thank you.

10:15.092 --> 10:16.746
[Tawny] Keep our boundaries,
you know?

10:16.877 --> 10:19.575
[uneasy music plays]

10:19.749 --> 10:22.796
♪

10:22.883 --> 10:25.407
[lock clicks, door opens,
keys jingling]

10:25.494 --> 10:27.627
♪

10:27.757 --> 10:28.758
[door closes]

10:28.932 --> 10:31.152
♪

10:31.282 --> 10:33.937
[footsteps approaching]

10:34.024 --> 10:36.853
♪

11:30.777 --> 11:33.518
[keyboard clacking]

11:33.693 --> 11:36.478
♪

11:46.836 --> 11:49.709
[sighs]

11:49.839 --> 11:52.494
[footsteps approaching]

11:54.322 --> 11:55.453
Iris Stanton?

11:55.584 --> 11:56.541
Yeah.

12:01.590 --> 12:04.506
[Iris] Sharp, ambitious,

12:04.636 --> 12:07.335
funny, hardworking.

12:09.250 --> 12:11.774
He always said, uh,
that architecture

12:11.905 --> 12:12.993
was an old man's game.

12:14.516 --> 12:15.647
He'd enjoy the irony.

12:17.388 --> 12:20.000
What medication
is he currently on?

12:20.130 --> 12:22.132
Uh, my sister
has that information.

12:22.263 --> 12:23.133
I can ask her right now.

12:23.264 --> 12:24.918
No rush.

12:25.005 --> 12:25.919
I won't lie to you.

12:26.049 --> 12:27.007
We have a waitlist,

12:27.094 --> 12:28.182
and it's already
quite extensive.

12:28.312 --> 12:29.749
Up to you.

12:29.836 --> 12:31.968
There are several
U.S.-based studies

12:32.099 --> 12:33.709
that might be worth
looking into.

12:33.840 --> 12:36.190
Yeah, I'll have to talk
to my sister about that.

12:36.277 --> 12:37.800
Brain health
is a global effort.

12:41.412 --> 12:42.936
Did you have
any other questions?

12:46.200 --> 12:48.158
Give me one reason why
we should get on that waitlist.

12:49.943 --> 12:51.858
Well, for better or worse,

12:51.988 --> 12:53.903
it's the most interdisciplinary

12:54.034 --> 12:55.862
participant-focused study
of its kind.

12:55.992 --> 12:58.212
What you see is what you get.

12:58.342 --> 13:01.258
We are overfunded,
if there is such a thing.

13:01.389 --> 13:02.869
The approach is holistic.

13:02.999 --> 13:04.653
We're looking at the disease

13:04.784 --> 13:07.438
as a neuroinflammatory response
in the microglia,

13:07.569 --> 13:09.136
the primary immune cells

13:09.266 --> 13:11.355
of the central nervous system
inside the brain.

13:11.486 --> 13:13.575
What about the protein buildup?

13:13.705 --> 13:16.273
We're all about inflammation
and the role that it plays

13:16.360 --> 13:18.232
in the acceleration
of the disease.

13:18.362 --> 13:20.800
It's a straight-up
Trojan horse approach.

13:20.930 --> 13:24.064
We introduce
a biodegradable nanoparticle

13:24.194 --> 13:27.502
the immune system will target
as friendly debris.

13:27.632 --> 13:29.852
Once the agent inside,
the nanoparticle, is released,

13:29.983 --> 13:31.898
it will interact
with the microglia

13:32.028 --> 13:34.030
and hopefully break the cycle

13:34.161 --> 13:36.467
of what's become a chronic
inflammatory response.

13:40.863 --> 13:43.387
So how many years
are we buying?

13:45.259 --> 13:47.522
If my father actually
gets into your study

13:47.609 --> 13:51.613
and if your drug
actually ends up working?

13:51.743 --> 13:53.963
What's it worth

13:54.094 --> 13:56.574
to potentially give a loved one
more time?

13:56.705 --> 13:58.359
The way I look at it,

13:58.446 --> 14:01.275
every clinical trial brings us,
all of us,

14:01.362 --> 14:04.669
one step closer
to where we'd like to be.

14:04.800 --> 14:08.369
-Even the ones that fail?
-Especially the ones that fail.

14:08.456 --> 14:12.808
There is clarity in realizing
that this isn't working.

14:12.939 --> 14:14.244
Let's try again.

14:19.946 --> 14:22.644
[cell phone buzzing]

14:25.125 --> 14:26.996
[Iris sighs softly]

14:27.127 --> 14:29.956
[buzzing continues]

14:30.086 --> 14:31.827
Hello?

14:31.958 --> 14:33.785
[Dad] Hello?

14:33.873 --> 14:35.526
Hello?

14:35.657 --> 14:37.441
-[Iris sighs]
-[Leanne] It's too early, Dad.

14:37.572 --> 14:39.269
She's still sleeping.

14:39.400 --> 14:41.141
I'm sorry, Iris.

14:41.271 --> 14:42.794
I'm in the middle
of clearing out.

14:42.882 --> 14:44.057
He keeps finding my phone.

14:44.187 --> 14:45.754
[Iris] No, that's okay.

14:45.885 --> 14:49.758
Um... what's going on?

14:49.889 --> 14:51.542
[Dad] There's a shadow
up on the wall.

14:51.629 --> 14:53.327
Is that coming
from the window?

14:53.457 --> 14:55.111
Uh, yeah, there's
a streetlight right there.

14:57.331 --> 14:59.681
-Do you see?
-Oh, I see.

14:59.811 --> 15:02.902
It's still dark out,
but I'm getting ready for work,

15:03.032 --> 15:04.991
so I'm drinking coffee.

15:05.121 --> 15:07.602
Oh, good.
I wouldn't mind some coffee.

15:07.689 --> 15:09.473
[Leanne chuckles]
Do you know what time it is?

15:09.560 --> 15:10.779
[Dad] No. What time is it?

15:10.910 --> 15:12.694
[Leanne laughs]

15:12.824 --> 15:14.826
I guess we can have
a decaf version of it here.

15:14.957 --> 15:16.350
-How about that?
-Oh, you should.

15:16.480 --> 15:18.047
Bedtime coffee is the best.

15:18.134 --> 15:20.180
Yes.
I think we absolutely should.

15:20.310 --> 15:23.052
[Leanne laughs]
Thanks for that, Izzy.

15:23.183 --> 15:26.534
[faucet runs, stops]

15:29.406 --> 15:30.712
Oh, I wouldn't mind
some coffee.

15:30.842 --> 15:32.844
[Leanne] Okay, Dad.

15:32.975 --> 15:35.325
You up to anything
exciting today?

15:35.456 --> 15:36.674
[Iris] You know...

15:36.805 --> 15:38.154
Do tell.

15:38.285 --> 15:39.939
[Iris] The usual.

15:40.026 --> 15:42.071
We're creating
a whole batch of new data

15:42.202 --> 15:44.465
so that the neural net
can train itself.

15:44.595 --> 15:46.728
[Leanne] Neural net?
That's AI, right?

15:46.858 --> 15:48.773
Yeah, it's the artificial
neural network.

15:48.904 --> 15:51.167
Neural network.
That... that sounds familiar.

15:51.298 --> 15:52.647
-[laughs]
-Does it?

15:52.734 --> 15:54.866
Well, it's... this.

15:54.997 --> 15:56.259
Yeah, that's right.

16:01.090 --> 16:02.439
[Dad] You know, my daughter,

16:02.570 --> 16:04.528
she knows
all about that stuff.

16:04.659 --> 16:07.270
She's very bright.

16:07.357 --> 16:09.229
Always was,
even as a young kid.

16:09.359 --> 16:11.666
Apple doesn't fall
far from the tree.

16:13.102 --> 16:15.365
She's... she's up in...

16:15.496 --> 16:17.628
[Dad grunts softly]

16:17.715 --> 16:19.021
...up in...

16:21.415 --> 16:24.418
...um...

16:24.548 --> 16:26.376
you know,

16:26.507 --> 16:29.771
finishing her masters,
wants to get her PhD.

16:29.858 --> 16:31.120
Isn't that something?

16:34.167 --> 16:35.820
-Really? Are you--
-[Dad] Yeah.

16:37.431 --> 16:38.867
[Iris] You're sure?

16:38.954 --> 16:41.435
Oh, yeah.

16:41.565 --> 16:43.350
I... I am very proud of her.

16:46.222 --> 16:47.702
You are?

16:50.052 --> 16:51.793
[Dad] She's very smart.

16:53.708 --> 16:55.188
Always was.

16:59.409 --> 17:01.150
Sorry.

17:01.281 --> 17:02.630
Maybe it's time
for a coffee break?

17:04.327 --> 17:05.328
[no audible dialogue]

17:06.677 --> 17:09.071
Well, um, the good news

17:09.202 --> 17:12.770
is that intelligence
is kind of hereditary.

17:14.555 --> 17:16.644
At least, half of it is,
anyway, so...

17:18.428 --> 17:19.864
[sighs]

17:19.995 --> 17:21.649
...she probably got
some of it from you.

17:25.479 --> 17:28.177
[uneasy music plays]

17:28.351 --> 17:31.180
♪

17:45.151 --> 17:46.456
You make me feel calm.

17:46.630 --> 17:48.719
♪

17:48.850 --> 17:50.025
I do?

17:50.199 --> 17:53.637
♪

17:53.768 --> 17:55.813
-You ever been with a Saudi?
-[Iris breathing heavily]

17:55.944 --> 17:58.990
-Is that a thing?
-Yeah, it is.

17:59.165 --> 18:01.993
♪

18:05.214 --> 18:07.564
No.

18:07.651 --> 18:10.045
And you're, um, you're Zahir?

18:10.132 --> 18:11.481
I'm whoever you want me to be.

18:11.655 --> 18:14.615
♪

18:14.702 --> 18:16.095
And who are you?

18:16.182 --> 18:19.010
♪

18:23.058 --> 18:24.886
-Cassie.
-[Zahir] Cassie.

18:25.060 --> 18:28.194
♪

18:28.324 --> 18:30.065
Can I call you something else?

18:30.239 --> 18:33.112
♪

18:39.640 --> 18:41.032
Iris.

18:45.820 --> 18:46.995
Okay, Iris.

18:49.867 --> 18:51.086
Let me see you.

18:58.006 --> 19:00.748
[distant engine revving]

19:29.298 --> 19:31.648
Let me see you for real.

19:36.131 --> 19:38.873
[mischievous music plays]

19:38.960 --> 19:41.876
♪

19:42.964 --> 19:46.402
[engine revving]

19:46.489 --> 19:49.275
♪

19:55.019 --> 19:58.240
[engines revving]

19:58.414 --> 20:01.374
♪

20:01.461 --> 20:04.420
[engines revving]

20:04.551 --> 20:07.249
[suspenseful music plays]

20:07.336 --> 20:10.209
♪

20:11.862 --> 20:14.909
[engines revving]

20:15.039 --> 20:17.390
[tires squealing]

20:17.564 --> 20:20.306
♪

20:31.230 --> 20:34.058
[dark music plays]

20:34.233 --> 20:37.018
♪

21:14.795 --> 21:16.405
[Iris] Emcee, can you hear me?

21:18.102 --> 21:20.844
[soft music plays]

21:20.975 --> 21:22.585
[Emcee] Hello.

21:22.672 --> 21:24.065
I don't think
we've met before.

21:24.195 --> 21:25.109
Who are you?

21:26.981 --> 21:28.243
We haven't.

21:28.374 --> 21:30.898
I'm just...

21:31.028 --> 21:33.204
I'm a friend.

21:33.292 --> 21:35.772
[Emcee] Oh. Hello, friend.

21:35.903 --> 21:37.513
I'm pleased
you came to see me.

21:37.644 --> 21:40.255
[dark music plays]

21:40.429 --> 21:42.997
♪

21:43.084 --> 21:46.348
We could just talk.

21:46.435 --> 21:48.785
[Emcee] Anything in particular
you'd like to talk about?

21:48.872 --> 21:51.701
♪

21:53.660 --> 21:56.576
Why don't you surprise me?

21:56.663 --> 21:58.665
[Emcee] Surprise in what way?

21:58.795 --> 22:01.537
Can you be more specific?

22:01.624 --> 22:04.584
♪

22:04.714 --> 22:05.628
[gasps]

22:07.587 --> 22:09.328
-[Leif] You okay?
-What time is it?

22:09.458 --> 22:11.286
[car alarm blaring
in the distance]

22:11.373 --> 22:12.679
[Leif] Oh, you have time.

22:14.507 --> 22:18.249
Not to give you cause
for alarm, but...

22:18.337 --> 22:21.775
we had a black SUV
following us last night

22:21.862 --> 22:23.516
and then again just now.

22:23.646 --> 22:24.908
[Iris] What, now?

22:24.995 --> 22:28.738
No, no, no. Not anymore.

22:28.825 --> 22:31.524
Was trailing us
for a good 20 minutes, though.

22:34.004 --> 22:38.269
[Iris] Um, did you get a look
at the driver?

22:38.357 --> 22:40.837
Mm.
Middle-aged lad, shaved head.

22:42.622 --> 22:43.884
[Iris] Did you get
the license plate?

22:44.014 --> 22:45.320
[Leif] I did.

22:45.494 --> 22:48.367
♪

22:50.281 --> 22:51.892
You want me to look into it?

22:54.242 --> 22:55.983
[Iris] No, that's okay. Just...

22:58.551 --> 23:00.553
...let me know
if it happens again.

23:00.683 --> 23:02.119
-[car horn honking]
-[Leif] I will.

23:05.122 --> 23:07.777
[soft tense music plays]

23:07.951 --> 23:11.041
♪

23:11.172 --> 23:13.609
[indistinct chatter]

23:13.783 --> 23:16.612
♪

23:20.529 --> 23:21.835
Thank you for doing this, Leif.

23:21.965 --> 23:23.271
No worries.

23:23.358 --> 23:26.187
♪

23:28.058 --> 23:29.233
[Hiram] Did you have fun
last night?

23:29.364 --> 23:30.234
[Iris] Why? Did you?

23:31.714 --> 23:32.759
[Hiram] Almond milk, no sugar.

23:32.889 --> 23:34.413
[Iris] Thanks.

23:34.543 --> 23:36.632
[Hiram]
Something looks different.

23:36.763 --> 23:39.287
Is it maybe your hair?

23:39.418 --> 23:41.594
Oh, it's the glasses. Got it.

23:41.681 --> 23:42.508
[device beeps]

23:42.682 --> 23:45.467
♪

23:48.035 --> 23:49.428
[Iris] Hi.

23:53.214 --> 23:55.172
It's good to see
your fucking face.

23:55.303 --> 23:57.958
Okay.

23:58.088 --> 23:59.307
Sometimes that's
all we want to hear

23:59.438 --> 24:01.048
from another person, right?

24:01.135 --> 24:04.747
We want them to express
what we're feeling.

24:04.878 --> 24:06.619
Right.

24:06.749 --> 24:08.664
Except in life, it doesn't
really work that way.

24:12.929 --> 24:14.975
It's a lot of desire
just poof, gone forever.

24:15.105 --> 24:17.151
[chuckles, sniffs]

24:17.281 --> 24:18.369
-Ah.
-[chuckles]

24:18.457 --> 24:20.371
Glad we sorted that out.
[laughs]

24:22.678 --> 24:26.987
Not getting what we want
is the easy part.

24:27.117 --> 24:30.643
Desire, once met, will
be succeeded by another desire.

24:30.773 --> 24:33.428
Once we get what we want,
we want something else.

24:36.605 --> 24:37.780
Hold that thought.

24:40.740 --> 24:43.438
[footsteps departing]

24:46.049 --> 24:48.704
[indistinct chatter]

25:00.237 --> 25:01.587
[Hiram]
Do you remember this thing?

25:04.328 --> 25:05.939
Yeah. What about it?

25:06.069 --> 25:07.549
[Hiram] The shuffle function.

25:07.636 --> 25:09.508
Total game changer. Come on.

25:09.638 --> 25:10.770
Don't tell me you didn't
have one of these.

25:10.900 --> 25:12.119
[Iris] I-I mean,
I had a Discman.

25:12.249 --> 25:13.512
That had a shuffle function.

25:13.642 --> 25:14.774
Right, but point being,

25:14.904 --> 25:17.080
it's a random,
ongoing sequence.

25:17.211 --> 25:18.560
Like a playlist?

25:18.647 --> 25:19.953
[Hiram] Or a play script.

25:20.083 --> 25:22.608
You know, another one
and another one

25:22.738 --> 25:26.481
and another one,
except once you press play...

25:26.612 --> 25:29.049
it's impossible to predict
what comes next.

25:29.136 --> 25:31.312
To keep us wanting more.

25:31.442 --> 25:33.749
[dramatic music plays]

25:33.880 --> 25:36.752
[no audible dialogue]

25:36.839 --> 25:39.712
♪

25:58.426 --> 26:01.516
[no audible dialogue]

26:01.647 --> 26:03.779
-You're being summoned.
-"Summoned"?

26:03.953 --> 26:05.128
♪

26:05.259 --> 26:06.347
[man] Car's waiting downstairs,

26:06.477 --> 26:08.392
so whenever you're ready...

26:08.523 --> 26:10.264
Wait, can you just tell me
what's going on?

26:10.394 --> 26:11.874
It's internal communication.

26:12.005 --> 26:13.833
I'm just the carrier.

26:13.963 --> 26:17.924
Um, is this an HR situation?

26:18.054 --> 26:19.795
Probably not.

26:19.926 --> 26:21.884
They would've sent someone
from HR.

26:22.015 --> 26:24.670
[tense music plays]

26:24.844 --> 26:27.629
♪
